description:
## Goal

Lift the heap-object size cap for real. Objects larger than `SIZE_TABLE[SIZE_TABLE.len()-1]` (~6 MiB) currently panic with "exceeds largest size class." This ticket routes those through a per-Heap fragment list — singleton allocations from the system allocator that participate in GC via a mark bit rather than being moved.

## Background

Today's grow path in `Heap::alloc` asserts `size <= SIZE_TABLE[last]`. This was the smallest-effort cleanup in fz-cty.1; the real lift was deferred to this ticket.

Cheney's correctness depends on every live object having a forwarding marker so re-encountered pointers resolve to the to-space copy. Multi-MB objects can't reasonably be copied through to-space — moving them every GC defeats the point of having them as singletons. The standard solution (BEAM's "heap fragments"): the fragment stays in place; the GC marks it visited; survivors persist, unmarked fragments are freed.

## Layout

`runtime/src/heap.rs`:

```rust
struct Fragment {
    ptr: *mut u8,        // start of allocation (= start of HeapHeader)
    size: usize,         // total bytes
    layout: Layout,      // for dealloc
    mark: bool,          // GC visited bit
}

pub struct Heap {
    /* existing fields */
    fragments: Vec<Fragment>,
}
```

## Alloc routing

`Heap::alloc(size)` for `size > SIZE_TABLE[last]`:

```rust
const FRAGMENT_THRESHOLD: usize = SIZE_TABLE[SIZE_TABLE.len() - 1];
if size > FRAGMENT_THRESHOLD {
    let aligned_size = (size + 15) & !15;  // 16-byte alignment for heap objects
    let layout = Layout::from_size_align(aligned_size, 16).expect("fragment layout");
    let ptr = unsafe { std::alloc::alloc_zeroed(layout) };
    assert!(!ptr.is_null(), "fragment allocation failed");
    self.fragments.push(Fragment { ptr, size: aligned_size, layout, mark: false });
    self.alloc_count += 1;
    return ptr as *mut HeapHeader;
}
// existing path (bump-or-grow within size-class block)
```

Skips bump_top advancement; fragment is its own allocation. Returns a pointer that satisfies the existing 16-byte alignment guarantee.

The `assert!(size <= new_size)` in the grow branch is **removed**. Oversized allocations never reach the grow path now.

## Cheney integration

`gc_with_extra_roots` and `gc_mid_flight`:

1. **GC start.** Reset `mark = false` on every fragment.
2. **from_ranges construction.** Existing logic adds block + abandoned_blocks ranges. Now also adds fragment ranges:
   ```rust
   for f in &self.fragments {
       from_ranges.push((f.ptr, unsafe { f.ptr.add(f.size) }));
   }
   ```
3. **`cheney_forward`.** When a pointer falls in a fragment range, do not copy. Set the fragment's mark bit. Push the pointer onto a parallel `frag_queue: Vec<*mut HeapHeader>` if not already visited. Return the pointer unchanged.

   Visited check: the mark bit doubles as the "already in queue" flag — only push if mark transitions false → true.

4. **After to-space BFS scan completes**, drain `frag_queue`. For each entry, call `cheney_trace_children` (which may push more entries onto either to-space's BFS frontier — wait, no, BFS for to-space is already drained — or onto frag_queue itself). Because BFS for to-space is done, fragment children that point into to-space were already traced by the time we got here; only fragment-to-fragment edges need extra processing.

   Actually safer: drain frag_queue interleaved with the BFS scan, not after. The simplest correct ordering:
   ```rust
   loop {
       // Drain any new to-space objects.
       while scan < free {
           cheney_trace_children(scan, ..., &mut frag_queue);
           scan = scan.add((*scan).size_bytes);
       }
       // Drain fragment queue.
       if let Some(f) = frag_queue.pop() {
           cheney_trace_children(f, ..., &mut frag_queue);
           continue;  // may push to free; check scan loop again
       }
       break;
   }
   ```
   Mixed-mode BFS: both queues run until both are empty.

5. **Post-scan sweep.** Walk `self.fragments`, free unmarked, reset marks on survivors:
   ```rust
   let mut i = 0;
   while i < self.fragments.len() {
       if self.fragments[i].mark {
           self.fragments[i].mark = false;
           i += 1;
       } else {
           let f = self.fragments.swap_remove(i);
           unsafe { std::alloc::dealloc(f.ptr, f.layout); }
       }
   }
   ```

## Heap::drop

Free all fragments before pool_free:

```rust
for f in self.fragments.drain(..) {
    unsafe { std::alloc::dealloc(f.ptr, f.layout); }
}
```

## Pointer classification helper

```rust
enum FromSource {
    InBlock,         // bump arena (current or abandoned)
    InFragment(usize),  // fragments[idx]
    OffHeap,         // static singletons (closures, etc.)
}

fn classify_from_ptr(p: *mut u8, from_block_ranges: &[(*mut u8, *mut u8)], fragments: &[Fragment]) -> FromSource;
```

`ptr_in_from_space` is split into the block check (existing behaviour) and the fragment check. Single function returns the enum so `cheney_forward` can route correctly.

## Cheney trace children — fragment-aware

`cheney_trace_children` doesn't need to know whether the object it's tracing is in to-space or a fragment — both have valid HeapHeaders and child layouts. The only difference is in `cheney_forward` (called for each child): a child pointing into a fragment marks-and-pushes rather than copying.

## Tests

- Alloc a 10 MiB struct → lands in fragments; `bytes_used()` reflects it (extend `bytes_used` to include fragment sizes).
- Root + GC: 10 MiB struct survives; mark bit cycles to false post-GC.
- Un-root + GC: 10 MiB struct freed (verify via memory accounting hook or by re-allocating and observing the address reuse — though malloc isn't deterministic, so just check the fragments Vec is empty).
- Multiple fragments: alloc three 10 MiB structs, root two, GC, verify one freed and two survive.
- Fragment → fragment edge: build a graph where one fragment's payload points at another fragment. Root the head, GC, verify both survive.
- Fragment → to-space edge: fragment points at a normal heap object. Root the fragment, GC, verify both survive and the heap object got moved into to-space normally.
- Heap::drop with live fragments: drop the heap, verify fragments are freed (system-allocator-managed; check via a custom Drop counter on a wrapper type).

## Three-path parity

All three paths reach `Heap::alloc` through the same API. No codegen change. The acceptance is "interp, JIT, and AOT can each allocate a 10 MiB struct and use it." A new fixture under `fixtures/large_object_via_fragment/` exercises this; runs across `[jit, interp, aot]`.

## Acceptance

- All new fragment tests pass.
- New fixture passes across the three paths.
- The old `#[should_panic(expected = "exceeds largest size class")]` test is **removed** (the behaviour it tested no longer exists).
- `Heap::drop` does not leak fragments (verified via tracing allocator or RAII counter).
- Clippy and warnings clean.

## Non-changes

- `MAX_HEAP_OBJECT_BYTES`: already removed in fz-cty.1; nothing to do.
- Block pool: unaffected.
- Shared zone / ProcBin / MSO: independent.
